        Determines whether the transposition or merge-and-split, Levenshtein state represented by (i,e,s) subsumes the other, represented by (j,f,t), under the maximum number of errors, n.
        Specified by:
        at in interface ISubsumesFunction
        Overrides:
        at in class SubsumesFunction
        Parameters:
        i - Index of the spelling candidate of the first position.
        e - Number of accumulated errors of the spelling candidate at index i of the first position.
        s - Either 0 or 1, depending on whether the first position is a regular state or a special case (e.g. transposition, merge, or split).
        j - Index of the spelling candidate of the second position.
        f - Number of accumulated errors of the spelling candidate at index j of the second position.
        t - Either 0 or 1, depending on whether the second position is a regular state or a special case (e.g. transposition, merge, or split).
        n - Maximum number of errors allowed in spelling candidates.
        Returns:
        Whether (i,e,s) subsumes (j,f,t)
